<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-606-622  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 606 622.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  August 29 1989* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>US military satellite proposed for Thai domestic use.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Cameron, Keith.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Stryker Group (telecommunication policy).andO;Topic:     ThailandPolicyTelecommunicationsSatellite CommunicationsMilitary.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>US MILITARY SATELLITE PROPOSED FOR THAI DOMESTIC USE BANGKOK, THAILAND, 1989AUG 25 (NB) -- A consortium led by the US Stryker Group has presented aproposal to the Thai Government which recommends the use of previouslyunavailable US military satellites for a domestic communications facility.andO;The project is estimated to cost about US$150 million.andP;  The consortium, whichincludes satellite launching specialist Ball Corporation, project managersBechtel and the world's largest private satellite operator Contel, plans toform a joint venture company with other Asian interests.andP;  This company willbe franchised with the operational management of the satellite, includingground services, and will be based in Hongkong.andP;  Earlier this year the ThaiGovernment was negotiating with AsiaSat, a Hughes satellite to be launched bythe Great Wall Company of China and managed by a consortium which includedinternational telecoms suppliers Cable and Wireless, the massive Li Ka Shingconglomerate Hutchison International and CITIC, mainland China's trading andinvestment operation.andP;  It is understood that the concept of utilizingtransponders on a satellite primarily intended for China fell out of favourin Thai military circles because of a perceived possibility of Chineseinfluence.andP;  This attitude was reinforced with the advent of the atrocities inBeijing in June.andP;  The Stryker proposal involves the use of a B-52 aircraftacting as the primary launch pad at 40,000 feet for the new Pegasus spacebooster.andP;  The 12-transponder satellite achieves geostationary orbit in a fewminutes, and at a fraction of the cost of traditional rocket launches.andO;(Keith Cameron/19890825)</TEXT></DOC>